{"cursor":"7589","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox language |name=Afar |nativename= |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic\n|states=Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti |region=Afar Triangle, North-Eastern Africa\n|speakers=1.4–1.5 million |fam2=Cushitic |fam3=East Cushitic |fam4=Lowland\nEast Cushitic |fam5=SahoâAfar |script=Ethiopic (in Ethiopia), Latin |minority=\n|iso1=aa|iso2=aar|iso3=aar |notice=IPA }}\n\n'Afar' () is a Lowland East Cushitic language spoken in Ethiopia, Eritrea and\nDjibouti. It is believed to have 1.5 million speakers, the Afar. The basic word\norder in Afar, like in other East Cushitic languages, is subjectâobjectâverb.\nIts speakers have a literacy rate of between one and three per cent. Its closest\nrelative is the Saho language. Raymond G. Gordon, Jr, ed. 2005. Ethnologue:\nLanguages of the World. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of\nLinguistics.\n\nIn Eritrea, Afar is recognized as one of nine national languages which formally\nenjoy equal status (though Tigrinya and Arabic are by far of greatest\nsignificance in official usage). There are daily broadcasts in the national\nradio and a translated version of the Eritrean constitution. In education,\nhowever, Afar speakers prefer Arabic â which many of them speak as a second\nlanguage â as the language of instruction. Marie-Claude Simeone-Senelle:\n[http://cy.revues.org/document39.html Les langues en ErythrÃ©e]. In: Chroniques\nYemÃ©nites 8, 2000  In the Afar Region of Ethiopia, Afar is partially used\nin some of the few\nschools, [http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=32048 Interview with\nAfar president]. IRIN News, 24 May 2002 while Amharic is the region's\nworking language. Ethiopian parliament:\n[http://www.ethiopar.net/type/English/basinfo/infoafar.htm The State of\nAfar]\n","linknr":245,"url":"Afar_language","recorded":1371243895,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Afar_language&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Afar_language&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/fav